# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-lightsail
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-lightsail] This is a **timeline of Amazon Web Services**, which offers a suite of cloud computing services that make up an on-demand computing platform.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:aws-lightsail/amazon-web-services] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] In 2011, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) identified five "essential characteristics" for cloud systems.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] By 2023, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) had expanded and refined the list.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The history of cloud computing extends to the 1960s, with the initial concepts of time-sharing becoming popularized via remote job entry (RJE).
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The "data center" model, where users submitted jobs to operators to run on mainframes, was predominantly used during this era.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] This period saw broad experimentation with making large-scale computing power more accessible through time-sharing, while optimizing infrastructure, platforms, and applications to improve efficiency for end users.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The "cloud" metaphor for virtualized services dates to 1994, when it was used by General Magic for the universe of "places" that mobile agents in the Telescript environment could "go".
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The metaphor is credited to David Hoffman, a General Magic communications specialist, based on its long-standing use in networking and telecom.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The expression *cloud computing* became more widely known in 1996 when Compaq Computer Corporation drew up a business plan for future computing and the Internet.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The company's ambition was to supercharge sales with "cloud computing-enabled applications".
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The business plan foresaw that online consumer file storage would likely be commercially successful.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] As a result, Compaq decided to sell server hardware to internet service providers.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] In the 2000s, the application of cloud computing began to take shape with the establishment of Amazon Web Services (AWS) in 2002, which allowed developers to build applications independently.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] In 2006 Amazon Simple Storage Service, known as Amazon S3, and the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) were released.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] In 2008 NASA's development of the first open-source software for deploying private and hybrid clouds.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The following decade saw the launch of various cloud services.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] In 2010, Microsoft launched Microsoft Azure, and Rackspace Hosting and NASA initiated an open-source cloud-software project, OpenStack.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] IBM introduced the IBM SmartCloud framework in 2011, and Oracle announced the Oracle Cloud in 2012.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] In December 2019, Amazon launched AWS Outposts, a service that extends AWS infrastructure, services, APIs, and tools to customer data centers, co-location spaces, or on-premises facilities.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Cloud computing can shorten time to market by offering pre-configured tools, scalable resources, and managed services, allowing users to focus on core business value rather than maintaining infrastructure.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms can enable organizations and individuals to reduce upfront capital expenditures on physical infrastructure by shifting to an operational expenditure model, where costs scale with usage.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms also offer managed services and tools, such as artificial intelligence, data analytics, and machine learning, which might otherwise require significant in-house expertise and infrastructure investment.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] While cloud computing can offer cost advantages through effective resource optimization, organizations often face challenges such as unused resources, inefficient configurations, and hidden costs without proper oversight and governance.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Many cloud platforms provide cost management tools, such as AWS Cost Explorer and Azure Cost Management, and frameworks like FinOps have emerged to standardize financial operations in the cloud.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Cloud computing also facilitates collaboration, remote work, and global service delivery by enabling secure access to data and applications from any location with an internet connection.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Cloud providers offer various redundancy options for core services, such as managed storage and managed databases, though redundancy configurations often vary by service tier.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Advanced redundancy strategies, such as cross-region replication or failover systems, typically require explicit configuration and may incur additional costs or licensing fees.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Cloud environments operate under a shared responsibility model, where providers are typically responsible for infrastructure security, physical hardware, and software updates, while customers are accountable for data encryption, identity and access management (IAM), and application-level security.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The decision to adopt cloud computing or maintain on-premises infrastructure depends on factors such as scalability, cost structure, latency requirements, regulatory constraints, and infrastructure customization.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Organizations with variable or unpredictable workloads, limited capital for upfront investments, or a focus on rapid scalability benefit from cloud adoption.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Startups, SaaS companies, and e-commerce platforms often prefer the pay-as-you-go operational expenditure (OpEx) model of cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies prioritizing global accessibility, remote workforce enablement, disaster recovery, and leveraging advanced services such as AI/ML and analytics are well-suited for the cloud.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] In recent years, some cloud providers have started offering specialized services for high-performance computing and low-latency applications, addressing some use cases previously exclusive to on-premises setups.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] On the other hand, organizations with strict regulatory requirements, highly predictable workloads, or reliance on deeply integrated legacy systems may find cloud infrastructure less suitable.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Businesses in industries like defense, government, or those handling highly sensitive data often favor on-premises setups for greater control and data sovereignty.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies with ultra-low latency requirements, such as high-frequency trading (HFT) firms, rely on custom hardware (e.g., FPGAs) and physical proximity to exchanges, which most cloud providers cannot fully replicate despite recent advancements.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Similarly, tech giants like Google, Meta, and Amazon build their own data centers due to economies of scale, predictable workloads, and the ability to customize hardware and network infrastructure for optimal efficiency.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] However, these companies also use cloud services selectively for certain workloads and applications where it aligns with their operational needs.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] In practice, many organizations are increasingly adopting hybrid cloud architectures, combining on-premises infrastructure with cloud services.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] This approach allows businesses to balance scalability, cost-effectiveness, and control, offering the benefits of both deployment models while mitigating their respective limitations.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] One of the primary challenges of cloud computing, compared with traditional on-premises systems, is maintaining data security and privacy.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Cloud users entrust their sensitive data to third-party providers, who may not have adequate measures to protect it from unauthorized access, breaches, or leaks.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Cloud users also face compliance risks if they have to adhere to certain regulations or standards regarding data protection, such as GDPR or HIPAA.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Another challenge of cloud computing is reduced visibility and control.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Cloud users may not have full insight into how their cloud resources are managed, configured, or optimized by their providers.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] They may also have limited ability to customize or modify their cloud services according to their specific needs or preferences.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Complete understanding of all technology may be impossible, especially given the scale, complexity, and deliberate opacity of contemporary systems; however, there is a need for understanding complex technologies and their interconnections to have power and agency within them.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The metaphor of the cloud can be seen as problematic as cloud computing retains the aura of something noumenal and numinous; it is something experienced without precisely understanding what it is or how it works.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Additionally, cloud migration is a significant challenge.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] This process involves transferring data, applications, or workloads from one cloud environment to another, or from on-premises infrastructure to the cloud.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Cloud migration can be complicated, time-consuming, and expensive, particularly when there are compatibility issues between different cloud platforms or architectures.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] If not carefully planned and executed, cloud migration can lead to downtime, reduced performance, or even data loss.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Applications hosted in the cloud are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] In a report by Gartner, a survey of 200 IT leaders revealed that 69% experienced budget overruns in their organizations' cloud expenditures during 2023.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Conversely, 31% of IT leaders whose organizations stayed within budget attributed their success to accurate forecasting and budgeting, proactive monitoring of spending, and effective optimization.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The 2024 Flexera State of Cloud Report identifies the top cloud challenges as managing cloud spend, followed by security concerns and lack of expertise.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Public cloud expenditures exceeded budgeted amounts by an average of 15%.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The report also reveals that cost savings is the top cloud initiative for 60% of respondents.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Furthermore, 65% measure cloud progress through cost savings, while 42% prioritize shorter time-to-market, indicating that cloud's promise of accelerated deployment is often overshadowed by cost concerns.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Typically, cloud providers' Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors, like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by service.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, the company typically does not offer monetary compensation.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Cloud computing abstractions aim to simplify resource management, but leaky abstractions can expose underlying complexities.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] These variations in abstraction quality depend on the cloud vendor, service and architecture.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Mitigating leaky abstractions requires users to understand the implementation details and limitations of the cloud services they utilize.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Service lock-in within the same vendor occurs when a customer becomes dependent on specific services within a cloud vendor, making it challenging to switch to alternative services within the same vendor when their needs change.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Cloud computing poses privacy concerns because the service provider can access the data that is in the cloud at any time.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] It could accidentally or deliberately alter or delete information.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Many cloud providers can share information with third parties if necessary for purposes of law and order without a warrant.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] That is permitted in their privacy policies, which users must agree to before they start using cloud services.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Solutions to privacy include policy and legislation as well as end-users' choices for how data is stored.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Users can encrypt data that is processed or stored within the cloud to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Identity management systems can also provide practical solutions to privacy concerns in cloud computing.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] These systems distinguish between authorized and unauthorized users and determine the amount of data that is accessible to each entity.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The systems work by creating and describing identities, recording activities, and getting rid of unused identities.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] According to the Cloud Security Alliance, the top three threats in the cloud are *Insecure Interfaces and APIs*, *Data Loss & Leakage*, and *Hardware Failure*—which accounted for 29%, 25% and 10% of all cloud security outages respectively.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Together, these form shared technology vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] In a cloud provider platform being shared by different users, there may be a possibility that information belonging to different customers resides on the same data server.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Additionally, Eugene Schultz, chief technology officer at Emagined Security, said that hackers are spending substantial time and effort looking for ways to penetrate the cloud.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] "There are some real Achilles' heels in the cloud infrastructure that are making big holes for the bad guys to get into".
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Because data from hundreds or thousands of companies can be stored on large cloud servers, hackers can theoretically gain control of huge stores of information through a single attack—a process he called "hyperjacking".
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Some examples of this include the Dropbox security breach, and iCloud 2014 leak.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Dropbox had been breached in October 2014, having over seven million of its users passwords stolen by hackers in an effort to get monetary value from it by Bitcoins (BTC).
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] By having these passwords, they are able to read private data as well as have this data be indexed by search engines (making the information public).
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] There is the problem of legal ownership of the data (If a user stores some data in the cloud, can the cloud provider profit from it?).
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Many Terms of Service agreements are silent on the question of ownership.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Physical control of the computer equipment (private cloud) is more secure than having the equipment off-site and under someone else's control (public cloud).
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] This delivers great incentive to public cloud computing service providers to prioritize building and maintaining strong management of secure services.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Some small businesses that do not have expertise in IT security could find that it is more secure for them to use a public cloud.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] There is the risk that end users do not understand the issues involved when signing on to a cloud service (persons sometimes do not read the many pages of the terms of service agreement, and just click "Accept" without reading).
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] This is important now that cloud computing is common and required for some services to work, for example for an intelligent personal assistant (Apple's Siri or Google Assistant).
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Fundamentally, private cloud is seen as more secure with higher levels of control for the owner, however public cloud is seen to be more flexible and requires less time and money investment from the user.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The attacks that can be made on cloud computing systems include man-in-the middle attacks, phishing attacks, authentication attacks, and malware attacks.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] One of the largest threats is considered to be malware attacks, such as Trojan horses.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Recent research conducted in 2022 has revealed that the Trojan horse injection method is a serious problem with harmful impacts on cloud computing systems.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from cloud providers, and courts can impose nondisclosure requirements preventing providers from notifying affected users.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] This framework is in legal tension with Article 48 of the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] As a result, cloud service providers operating in both Europe and the U.S. may face competing legal obligations.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Donohue writing for the *Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy*, cloud service providers also fall within the broader category of service providers subject to Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA), which has had documented effects on cloud providers and their customers.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The National Institute of Standards and Technology recognized three cloud service models in 2011: Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS).
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) later identified additional models in 2023, including "Network as a Service", "Communications as a Service", "Compute as a Service", and "Data Storage as a Service".
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) refers to online services that provide high-level APIs used to abstract various low-level details of underlying network infrastructure like physical computing resources, location, data partitioning, scaling, security, backup, etc.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] A hypervisor runs the virtual machines as guests.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Pools of hypervisors within the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to customers' varying requirements.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Linux containers run in isolated partitions of a single Linux kernel running directly on the physical hardware.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Linux cgroups and namespaces are the underlying Linux kernel technologies used to isolate, secure and manage the containers.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The use of containers offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The NIST's definition of cloud computing describes IaaS as "where the consumer is able to deploy and run arbitrary software, which can include operating systems and applications.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] IaaS-cloud providers supply these resources on-demand from their large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks).
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] To deploy their applications, cloud users install operating-system images and their application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] In this model, the cloud user patches and maintains the operating systems and the application software.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Cloud providers typically bill IaaS services on a utility computing basis: cost reflects the number of resources allocated and consumed.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] PaaS vendors offer a development environment to application developers.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The provider typically develops toolkit and standards for development and channels for distribution and payment.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] In the PaaS models, cloud providers deliver a computing platform, typically including an operating system, programming-language execution environment, database, and the web server.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Application developers develop and run their software on a cloud platform instead of directly buying and managing the underlying hardware and software layers.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] With some PaaS, the underlying computer and storage resources scale automatically to match application demand so that the cloud user does not have to allocate resources manually.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Some integration and data management providers also use specialized applications of PaaS as delivery models for data.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Examples include **iPaaS (Integration Platform as a Service)** and **dPaaS (Data Platform as a Service)**. iPaaS enables customers to develop, execute and govern integration flows.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Under the iPaaS integration model, customers drive the development and deployment of integrations without installing or managing any hardware or middleware. dPaaS delivers integration—and data-management—products as a fully managed service.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Under the dPaaS model, the PaaS provider, not the customer, manages the development and execution of programs by building data applications for the customer. dPaaS users access data through data-visualization tools.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] In the software as a service (SaaS) model, users gain access to application software and databases.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Cloud providers manage the infrastructure and platforms that run the applications.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] SaaS is sometimes referred to as "on-demand software" and is usually priced on a pay-per-use basis or using a subscription fee.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] In the SaaS model, cloud providers install and operate application software in the cloud and cloud users access the software from cloud clients.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Cloud users do not manage the cloud infrastructure and platform where the application runs.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] This eliminates the need to install and run the application on the cloud user's own computers, which simplifies maintenance and support.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Cloud applications differ from other applications in their scalability—which can be achieved by cloning tasks onto multiple virtual machines at run-time to meet changing work demand.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Load balancers distribute the work over the set of virtual machines.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] This process is transparent to the cloud user, who sees only a single access-point.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] To accommodate a large number of cloud users, cloud applications can be *multitenant*, meaning that any machine may serve more than one cloud-user organization.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The pricing model for SaaS applications is typically a monthly or yearly flat fee per user, so prices become scalable and adjustable if users are added or removed at any point.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Proponents claim that SaaS gives a business the potential to reduce IT operational costs by outsourcing hardware and software maintenance and support to the cloud provider.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] This enables the business to reallocate IT operations costs away from hardware/software spending and from personnel expenses, towards meeting other goals.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] In addition, with applications hosted centrally, updates can be released without the need for users to install new software.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] One drawback of SaaS comes with storing the users' data on the cloud provider's server.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] As a result, there could be unauthorized access to the data.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Examples of applications offered as SaaS are games and productivity software like Google Docs and Office Online.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] SaaS applications may be integrated with cloud storage or File hosting services, which is the case with Google Docs being integrated with Google Drive, and Office Online being integrated with OneDrive.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Serverless computing allows customers to use various cloud capabilities without the need to provision, deploy, or manage hardware or software resources, apart from providing their application code or data.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] ISO/IEC 22123-2:2023 classifies serverless alongside Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS) under the broader category of cloud service categories.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Notably, while ISO refers to these classifications as cloud service categories, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) refers to them as service models.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] "A cloud deployment model represents the way in which cloud computing can be organized based on the control and sharing of physical or virtual resources." Cloud deployment models define the fundamental patterns of interaction between cloud customers and cloud providers.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] They do not detail implementation specifics or the configuration of resources.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Private cloud is cloud infrastructure operated solely for a single organization, whether managed internally or by a third party, and hosted either internally or externally.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Undertaking a private cloud project requires significant engagement to virtualize the business environment, and requires the organization to reevaluate decisions about existing resources.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] It can improve business, but every step in the project raises security issues that must be addressed to prevent serious vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Self-run data centers are generally capital intensive.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] They have a significant physical footprint, requiring allocations of space, hardware, and environmental controls.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] These assets have to be refreshed periodically, resulting in additional capital expenditures.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] They have attracted criticism because users "still have to buy, build, and manage them" and thus do not benefit from less hands-on management, essentially "[lacking] the economic model that makes cloud computing such an intriguing concept".
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Cloud services are considered "public" when they are delivered over the public Internet, and they may be offered as a paid subscription, or free of charge.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Architecturally, there are few differences between public- and private-cloud services, but security concerns increase substantially when services (applications, storage, and other resources) are shared by multiple customers.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Most public-cloud providers offer direct-connection services that allow customers to securely link their legacy data centers to their cloud-resident applications.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Several factors like the functionality of the solutions, cost, integrational and organizational aspects as well as safety & security are influencing the decision of enterprises and organizations to choose a public cloud or on-premises solution.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Varied use cases for hybrid cloud composition exist.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] For example, an organization may store sensitive client data in house on a private cloud application, but interconnect that application to a business intelligence application provided on a public cloud as a software service.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] This example of hybrid cloud extends the capabilities of the enterprise to deliver a specific business service through the addition of externally available public cloud services.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Hybrid cloud adoption depends on a number of factors such as data security and compliance requirements, level of control needed over data, and the applications an organization uses.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Another example of hybrid cloud is one where IT organizations use public cloud computing resources to meet temporary capacity needs that can not be met by the private cloud.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] This capability enables hybrid clouds to employ cloud bursting for scaling across clouds.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting is an application deployment model in which an application runs in a private cloud or data center and "bursts" to a public cloud when the demand for computing capacity increases.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] A primary advantage of cloud bursting and a hybrid cloud model is that an organization pays for extra compute resources only when they are needed.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting enables data centers to create an in-house IT infrastructure that supports average workloads, and use cloud resources from public or private clouds, during spikes in processing demands.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] As a result, only a portion of the potential cost savings of cloud computing is achieved.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] According to ISO/IEC 22123-1: "multi-cloud is a cloud deployment model in which a customer uses public cloud services provided by two or more cloud service providers".
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Poly cloud refers to the use of multiple public clouds for the purpose of leveraging specific services that each provider offers.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] It differs from Multi cloud in that it is not designed to increase flexibility or mitigate against failures but is rather used to allow an organization to achieve more than could be done with a single provider.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] According to International Data Corporation (IDC), global spending on cloud computing services has reached $706 billion and is expected to reach $1.3 trillion by 2025.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Gartner estimated that global public cloud services end-user spending would reach $600 billion by 2023.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] According to a McKinsey & Company report, cloud cost-optimization levers and value-oriented business use cases foresee more than $1 trillion in run-rate EBITDA across Fortune 500 companies as up for grabs in 2030.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] In 2022, more than $1.3 trillion in enterprise IT spending was at stake from the shift to the cloud, growing to almost $1.8 trillion in 2025, according to Gartner.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The *Communication* set out a series of "digital agenda actions" which the Commission proposed to undertake in order to support the development of a fair and effective market for cloud computing services.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] As of 2025, the three largest cloud computing providers by market share, commonly referred to as hyperscalers, are Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] These companies dominate the global cloud market due to their extensive infrastructure, broad service offerings, and scalability.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] In recent years, organizations have increasingly adopted alternative cloud providers, which offer specialized services that distinguish them from hyperscalers.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Alternative cloud providers are often part of multi-cloud strategies, where organizations use multiple cloud services—both from hyperscalers and specialized providers—to optimize performance, compliance, and cost efficiency.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] However, they do not necessarily serve as direct replacements for hyperscalers, as their offerings are typically more specialized.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The goal of cloud computing is to allow users to take benefit from all of these technologies, without the need for deep knowledge about or expertise with each one of them.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The cloud aims to cut costs and helps the users focus on their core business instead of being impeded by IT obstacles.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] The main enabling technology for cloud computing is virtualization.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Virtualization software separates a physical computing device into one or more "virtual" devices, each of which can be easily used and managed to perform computing tasks.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] With operating system-level virtualization essentially creating a scalable system of multiple independent computing devices, idle computing resources can be allocated and used more efficiently.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Virtualization provides the agility required to speed up IT operations and reduces cost by increasing infrastructure utilization.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Autonomic computing automates the process through which the user can provision resources on-demand.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] By minimizing user involvement, automation speeds up the process, reduces labor costs and reduces the possibility of human errors.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Cloud computing uses concepts from utility computing to provide metrics for the services used.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-computing] Cloud computing attempts to address QoS (quality of service) and reliability problems of other grid computing models.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Public clouds are managed by cloud service providers, which operate the underlying infrastructure such as servers, storage, networking, and data center facilities.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Users may also opt to manage their public cloud services with a third-party cloud management tool.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Managing a private cloud requires software tools to help create a virtualized pool of compute resources, provide a self-service portal for end users and handle security, resource allocation, tracking and billing.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Management tools for private clouds tend to be service driven, as opposed to resource driven, because cloud environments are typically highly virtualized and organized in terms of portable workloads.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] In hybrid cloud environments, compute, network and storage resources must be managed across multiple domains, so a good management strategy should start by defining what needs to be managed, and where and how to do it.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Policies to help govern these domains should include configuration and installation of images, access control, and budgeting and reporting.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Access control often includes the use of Single sign-on (SSO), in which a user logs in once and gains access to all systems without being prompted to log in again at each of them.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Cloud management combines software and technologies in a design for managing cloud environments.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Software developers have responded to the management challenges of cloud computing with a variety of cloud management platforms and tools.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] These tools include native tools offered by public cloud providers as well as third-party tools designed to provide consistent functionality across multiple cloud providers.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Administrators must balance the competing requirements of efficient consistency across different cloud platforms with access to different native functionality within individual cloud platforms.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] The growing acceptance of public cloud and increased multicloud usage is driving the need for consistent cross-platform management.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Rapid adoption of cloud services is introducing a new set of management challenges for those technical professionals responsible for managing IT systems and services.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Cloud-management platforms and tools should have the ability to provide minimum functionality in the following categories.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Functionality can be both natively provided or orchestrated via third-party integration.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Organizations may group these criteria into key use cases including Cloud Brokerage, DevOps Automation, Governance, and Day-2 Life Cycle Operations.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] High-end cloud management tools should also have the ability to handle system failures automatically with capabilities such as self-monitoring, an explicit notification mechanism, and include failover and self-healing capabilities.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Legacy management infrastructures, which are based on the concept of dedicated system relationships and architecture constructs, are not well suited to cloud environments where instances are continually launched and decommissioned.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Instead, the dynamic nature of cloud computing requires monitoring and management tools that are adaptable, extensible and customizable.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Cloud computing presents a number of management challenges.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Companies using public clouds do not have ownership of the equipment hosting the cloud environment, and because the environment is not contained within their own networks, public cloud customers do not have full visibility or control.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Users of public cloud services must also integrate with an architecture defined by the cloud provider, using its specific parameters for working with cloud components.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Integration includes tying into the cloud APIs for configuring IP addresses, subnets, firewalls and data service functions for storage.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Because control of these functions is based on the cloud provider’s infrastructure and services, public cloud users must integrate with the cloud infrastructure management.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Capacity management is a challenge for both public and private cloud environments because end users have the ability to deploy applications using self-service portals.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Applications of all sizes may appear in the environment, consume an unpredictable amount of resources, then disappear at any time.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] A possible solution is profiling the applications impact on computational resources.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] As result, the performance models allow the prediction of how resource utilization changes according to application patterns.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Thus, resources can be dynamically scaled to meet the expected demand.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] This is critical to cloud providers that need to provision resources quickly to meet a growing demand by their applications.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Charge-back—or, pricing resource use on a granular basis—is a challenge for both public and private cloud environments.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Charge-back is a challenge for public cloud service providers because they must price their services competitively while still creating profit.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Users of public cloud services may find charge-back challenging because it is difficult for IT groups to assess actual resource costs on a granular basis due to overlapping resources within an organization that may be paid for by an individual business unit, such as electrical power.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] For private cloud operators, charge-back is fairly straightforward, but the challenge lies in guessing how to allocate resources as closely as possible to actual resource usage to achieve the greatest operational efficiency.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Hybrid cloud environments, which combine public and private cloud services, sometimes with traditional infrastructure elements, present their own set of management challenges.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] These include security concerns if sensitive data lands on public cloud servers, budget concerns around overuse of storage or bandwidth and proliferation of mismanaged images.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Managing the information flow in a hybrid cloud environment is also a significant challenge.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] On-premises clouds must share information with applications hosted off-premises by public cloud providers, and this information may change constantly.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Hybrid cloud environments also typically include a complex mix of policies, permissions and limits that must be managed consistently across both public and private clouds.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] CMPs provide a means for a cloud service customer to manage the deployment and operation of applications and associated datasets across multiple cloud service infrastructures, including both on-premises cloud infrastructure and public cloud service provider infrastructure.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] In other words, CMPs provide management capabilities for hybrid cloud and multi-cloud environments.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] A cloud management platform (CMP) provides broad cloud management functionality atop both public cloud provider platforms and private cloud platforms.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] CMPs manage cloud services and resources that are distributed across multiple cloud platforms.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] The value of CMPs stands in delivering the maximum level of consistency between platforms without compromising depth of functionality.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Unfortunately, the meaning of the term "cloud management platform" (CMP) has evolved over the past decade so that the precise meaning of this term is often unclear in discussions of management strategy.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] One vendor using this term may mean something completely different from another.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Selecting the right management approach for cloud services is therefore a complex task.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Providers and vendors can further confuse the evaluation by highlighting only their strengths and avoiding their weaknesses.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Furthermore, each provider and vendor focuses on solving different aspects of cloud management, making it difficult to compare solutions.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] A minimum viable CMP must be able to provide support for all technology stack layers and orchestrate capabilities across them (IaaS, PaaS, SaaS, etc.) It must include a cloud-agnostic tool to support portability/migration to and across hybrid clouds.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] An integration framework will take advantage of existing automation tools used internally and combine these with new CMP features.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] The ability to provide native container support across virtual technologies is a prerequisite, and CMPs are now either container ‘native’ (architected using containers) or being reengineered to support containers.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Along with standard OS deployments, a CMP’s blueprinting function will enable administrators to create and provide image-based solutions and customized configurations.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Integration with other IT assets and databases (CMDB) and role-based access control and governance are key.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] As a consolidated control plane for IT operations, one of the primary roles of a CMP is the integration of existing application lifecycle tools, hypervisors, and cloud platforms.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Given that charter, CMPs must integrate with internal and external systems to manage multi-cloud services.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] The ability to support both published APIs and provide for customization, if needed, is a critical capability.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Like any other brokerage firm, a Cloud Services Brokerage (CSB) manages cloud services for clients.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Gartner explains that CSBs play an intermediary role in the cloud computing management process.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Since there are many Datacenters hosting the provided applications, the role of a service broker becomes very important in choosing the most suitable data center to serve the received request.
[src:aws-lightsail/cloud-management] Cloud services brokerages consolidate cloud services from one or more sources and allow customers to access these services through one portal.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] In computing, **virtualization** (or **virtualisation** in Commonwealth English; see spelling differences,) abbreviated as **v12n**, is a series of technologies that allows dividing of physical computing resources into a series of virtual machines, operating systems, processes or containers.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Virtualization began in the 1960s with IBM CP/CMS.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] The control program CP provided each user with a simulated stand-alone System/360 computer.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] In hardware virtualization, the *host machine* is the machine that is used by the virtualization and the *guest machine* is the virtual machine.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] The words *host* and *guest* are used to distinguish the software that runs on the physical machine from the software that runs on the virtual machine.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] The software or firmware that creates a virtual machine on the host hardware is called a *hypervisor* or *virtual machine monitor*.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Hardware virtualization is not the same as hardware emulation.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization facilitates building a virtual machine monitor and allows guest OSes to be run in isolation.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Desktop virtualization is the concept of separating the logical desktop from the physical machine.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Operating system-level virtualization, also known as containerization, refers to an operating system feature in which the kernel allows the existence of multiple isolated user-space instances.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] The usual goal of virtualization is to centralize administrative tasks while improving scalability and overall hardware-resource utilization.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] A form of virtualization was first demonstrated with IBM's CP-40 research system in 1967, then distributed via open source in CP/CMS in 1967–1972, and re-implemented in IBM's VM family from 1972 to the present.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Each CP/CMS user was provided a simulated, stand-alone computer.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Each such virtual machine had the complete capabilities of the underlying machine, and (for its user) the virtual machine was indistinguishable from a private system.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] This simulation was comprehensive, and was based on the *Principles of Operation* manual for the hardware.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] It thus included such elements as an instruction set, main memory, interrupts, exceptions, and device access.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] The result was a single machine that could be multiplexed among many users.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization first appeared on the IBM System/370 in 1972, for use with VM/370, the first virtual machine operating system.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] IBM added virtual memory hardware to the System/370 series in 1972 which is not the same as Intel VT-x Rings providing a higher privilege level for Hypervisor to properly control Virtual Machines requiring full access to Supervisor and Program or User modes.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] With the increasing demand for high-definition computer graphics (e.g.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] CAD), virtualization of mainframes lost some attention in the late 1970s, when the upcoming minicomputers fostered resource allocation through distributed computing, encompassing the commoditization of microcomputers.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] The increase in compute capacity per x86 server (and in particular the substantial increase in modern networks' bandwidths) rekindled interest in data-center based computing which is based on virtualization techniques.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] The primary driver was the potential for server consolidation: virtualization allowed a single server to cost-efficiently consolidate compute power on multiple underutilized dedicated servers.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] The most visible hallmark of a return to the roots of computing is cloud computing, which is a synonym for data center based computing (or mainframe-like computing) through high bandwidth networks.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] It is closely connected to virtualization.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] This made it difficult to implement a virtual machine monitor for this type of processor.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Specific limitations included the inability to trap on some privileged instructions.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Therefore, to compensate for these architectural limitations, designers accomplished virtualization of the x86 architecture through two methods: **full virtualization** or **paravirtualization**.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Both create the illusion of physical hardware to achieve the goal of operating system independence from the hardware but present some trade-offs in performance and complexity.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Full virtualization was not fully available on the x86 platform prior to 2005.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Many platform hypervisors for the x86 platform came very close and claimed full virtualization (such as Adeos, Mac-on-Linux, Parallels Desktop for Mac, Parallels Workstation, VMware Workstation, VMware Server (formerly GSX Server), VirtualBox, Win4BSD, and Win4Lin Pro).
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] In 2005 and 2006, Intel and AMD (working independently) created new processor extensions to the x86 architecture called Intel VT-x and AMD-V, respectively.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] On the Itanium architecture, hardware-assisted virtualization is known as VT-i.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Software executed on these virtual machines is separated from the underlying hardware resources.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] For example, a computer that is running Arch Linux may host a virtual machine that looks like a computer with the Microsoft Windows operating system; Windows-based software can be run on the virtual machine.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Full virtualization employs techniques that pools physical computer resources into one or more instances; each running a virtual environment where any software or operating system capable of execution on the raw hardware can be run in the virtual machine.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Two common full virtualization techniques are typically used: (a) binary translation and (b) hardware-assisted full virtualization.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Binary translation automatically modifies the software on-the-fly to replace instructions that "pierce the virtual machine" with a different, virtual machine safe sequence of instructions.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization allows guest operating systems to be run in isolation with virtually no modification to the (guest) operating system.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] This approach was pioneered in 1966 with the IBM CP-40 and CP-67, predecessors of the VM family.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Some hypervisors perform binary translation between guest and host, either between differing instruction set architectures or between a guest and host using the same instruction set.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] The hypervisor may be designed to interpret a guest's machine code directly or generate machine code for the host's architecture in a form of dynamic binary translation.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Most common hypervisors, including ones that use hardware to assist virtualization, perform binary translation of some instructions relating to hardware access.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] In such a case, the hypervisor will trap the instruction and perform the functions to emulate the required devices.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Hypervisors that perform binary translation may also be designed to substitute instructions within the guest context to aid security or performance.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization (or *accelerated virtualization; Xen calls it hardware virtual machine (HVM), and Virtual Iron calls it native virtualization)* is a way of improving overall efficiency of hardware virtualization using help from the host processors.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] A full virtualization is used to emulate a complete hardware environment, or virtual machine, in which an unmodified guest operating system (using the same instruction set as the host machine) effectively executes in complete isolation.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization was first introduced on the IBM 308X processors in 1980, with the Start Interpretive Execution (SIE) instruction.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] It was added to x86 processors (Intel VT-x, AMD-V or VIA VT) in 2005, 2006 and 2010 respectively.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] IBM offers hardware virtualization for its IBM Power Systems hardware for AIX, Linux and IBM i, and for its IBM Z mainframes.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] IBM refers to its specific form of hardware virtualization as "logical partition", or more commonly as LPAR.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization reduces the maintenance overhead of binary translation based virtualization as it reduces (ideally, eliminates) the code that needs to be translated in the guest operating system.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] It is also considerably easier to obtain better performance.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Paravirtualization is a virtualization technique that presents a software interface to the virtual machines which is similar, yet not identical, to the underlying hardware–software interface.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Paravirtualization improves performance and efficiency, compared to full virtualization, by having the guest operating system communicate with the hypervisor.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] By allowing the guest operating system to indicate its intent to the hypervisor, each can cooperate to obtain better performance when running in a virtual machine.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] The intent of the modified interface is to reduce the portion of the guest's execution time spent performing operations which are substantially more difficult to run in a virtual environment compared to a non-virtualized environment.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] The paravirtualization provides specially defined 'hooks' to allow the guest(s) and host to request and acknowledge these tasks, which would otherwise be executed in the virtual domain (where execution performance is worse).
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] A successful paravirtualized platform may allow the virtual machine monitor (VMM) to be simpler (by relocating execution of critical tasks from the virtual domain to the host domain), and/or reduce the overall performance degradation of machine execution inside the virtual guest.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Paravirtualization requires the guest operating system to be explicitly ported for the para-API – a conventional OS distribution that is not paravirtualization-aware can still run on a paravirtualizing VMM.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] However, even in cases where the operating system cannot be modified, components may be available that enable many of the significant performance advantages of paravirtualization.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] For example, the Xen Windows GPLPV project provides a kit of paravirtualization-aware device drivers, that are intended to be installed into a Microsoft Windows virtual guest running on the Xen hypervisor.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Such applications tend to be accessible through the paravirtual machine interface environment.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] This ensures run-mode compatibility across multiple encryption algorithm models, allowing seamless integration within the paravirtual framework.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] The term "paravirtualization" was first used in the research literature in association with the Denali Virtual Machine Manager.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] The term is also used to describe the Xen, L4, TRANGO, VMware, Wind River and XtratuM hypervisors.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] All these projects use or can use paravirtualization techniques to support high performance virtual machines on x86 hardware by implementing a virtual machine that does not implement the hard-to-virtualize parts of the actual x86 instruction set.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] In 2005, VMware proposed a paravirtualization interface, the Virtual Machine Interface (VMI), as a communication mechanism between the guest operating system and the hypervisor.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] This interface enabled transparent paravirtualization in which a single binary version of the operating system can run either on native hardware or on a hypervisor in paravirtualized mode.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] The first appearance of paravirtualization support in Linux occurred with the merge of the ppc64 port in 2002, which supported running Linux as a paravirtualized guest on IBM pSeries (RS/6000) and iSeries (AS/400) hardware.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] At the USENIX conference in 2006 in Boston, Massachusetts, a number of Linux development vendors (including IBM, VMware, Xen, and Red Hat) collaborated on an alternative form of paravirtualization, initially developed by the Xen group, called "paravirt-ops".
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] The paravirt-ops code (often shortened to pv-ops) was included in the mainline Linux kernel as of the 2.6.23 version, and provides a hypervisor-agnostic interface between the hypervisor and guest kernels.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Distribution support for pv-ops guest kernels appeared starting with Ubuntu 7.04 and RedHat 9.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Xen hypervisors based on any 2.6.24 or later kernel support pv-ops guests, as does VMware's Workstation product beginning with version 6.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Hybrid virtualization combines full virtualization techniques with paravirtualized drivers to overcome limitations with hardware-assisted full virtualization.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] A hardware-assisted full virtualization approach uses an unmodified guest operating system that involves many VM traps producing high CPU overheads limiting scalability and the efficiency of server consolidation.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] The hybrid virtualization approach overcomes this problem.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Desktop virtualization separates the logical desktop from the physical machine.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] One form of desktop virtualization, virtual desktop infrastructure (VDI), can be thought of as a more advanced form of hardware virtualization.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Rather than interacting with a host computer directly via a keyboard, mouse, and monitor, the user interacts with the host computer using another desktop computer or a mobile device by means of a network connection, such as a LAN, Wireless LAN or even the Internet.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] In addition, the host computer in this scenario becomes a server computer capable of hosting multiple virtual machines at the same time for multiple users.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Companies like HP and IBM provide a hybrid VDI model with a range of virtualization software and delivery models to improve upon the limitations of distributed client computing.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Selected client environments move workloads from PCs and other devices to data center servers, creating well-managed virtual clients, with applications and client operating environments hosted on servers and storage in the data center.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] For users, this means they can access their desktop from any location, without being tied to a single client device.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Since the resources are centralized, users moving between work locations can still access the same client environment with their applications and data.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] For IT administrators, this means a more centralized, efficient client environment that is easier to maintain and able to more quickly respond to the changing needs of the user and business.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Another form, session virtualization, allows multiple users to connect and log into a shared but powerful computer over the network and use it simultaneously.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Each is given a desktop and a personal folder in which they store their files.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] With multiseat configuration, session virtualization can be accomplished using a single PC with multiple monitors, keyboards, and mice connected.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Thin clients, which are seen in desktop virtualization, are simple and/or cheap computers that are primarily designed to connect to the network.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] They may lack significant hard disk storage space, RAM or even processing power, but many organizations are beginning to look at the cost benefits of eliminating "thick client" desktops that are packed with software (and require software licensing fees) and making more strategic investments.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Desktop virtualization simplifies software versioning and patch management, where the new image is simply updated on the server, and the desktop gets the updated version when it reboots.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] It also enables centralized control over what applications the user is allowed to have access to on the workstation.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Moving virtualized desktops into the cloud creates hosted virtual desktops (HVDs), in which the desktop images are centrally managed and maintained by a specialist hosting firm.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Benefits include scalability and the reduction of capital expenditure, which is replaced by a monthly operational cost.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Such instances, called containers, partitions, virtual environments (VEs) or jails (FreeBSD jail or chroot jail), may look like (physical) computers from the point of view of programs running in them.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] A computer program running on an ordinary operating system can see all resources (connected devices, files and folders, network shares, CPU power, quantifiable hardware capabilities) of that computer.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] However, programs running inside a container can only see the container's contents and devices assigned to the container.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] This provides many of the benefits that virtual machines have such as standardization and scalability, while using less resources as the kernel is shared between containers.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Containerization started gaining prominence in 2014, with the introduction of Docker.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] A common goal of virtualization is to centralize administrative tasks while improving scalability and overall hardware-resource utilization.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] With virtualization, several operating systems can be run in parallel on a single central processing unit (CPU).
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] This parallelism tends to reduce overhead costs and differs from multitasking, which involves running several programs on the same OS.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Using virtualization, an enterprise can better manage updates and rapid changes to the operating system and applications without disrupting the user.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Ultimately, virtualization dramatically improves the efficiency and availability of resources and applications in an organization.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Instead of relying on the old model of "one server, one application" that leads to underutilized resources, virtual resources are dynamically applied to meet business needs without any excess fat".
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] Virtual machines running proprietary operating systems require licensing, regardless of the host machine's operating system.
[src:aws-lightsail/virtualization] For example, installing Microsoft Windows into a VM guest requires its licensing requirements to be satisfied.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] A **web application** (or **web app**) is application software that is created with web technologies and runs via a web browser.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] Web applications emerged during the late 1990s and allowed for the server to dynamically build a response to the request, in contrast to static web pages.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] Web applications are commonly distributed via a web server.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] There are several different tier systems that web applications use to communicate between the web browsers, the client interface, and server data.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] Each system has its own uses as they function in different ways.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] However, there are many security risks that developers must be aware of during development; proper measures to protect user data are vital.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] Web applications are often constructed with the use of a web application framework.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] Single-page applications (SPAs) and progressive web apps (PWAs) are two architectural approaches to creating web applications that provide a user experience similar to native apps, including features such as smooth navigation, offline support, and faster interactions.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] Modern browsers such as Chrome offer sandboxing for every browser tab which improves security and restricts access to local resources.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] No software installation is required as the app runs within the browser which reduces the need for managing software installations.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] With the use of remote cloud services, customers do not need to manage servers as that can be left to the developer and the cloud service and can use the software with a relatively low power, low-resource PC such as a thin client.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] The source code of the application can stay the same across operating systems and devices of users with the use of responsive web design, since it only needs to be compatible with web browsers which adhere to web standards, making the code highly portable and saving on development time.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] Numerous JavaScript frameworks and CSS frameworks facilitate development.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] The concept of a "web application" was first introduced in the Java language in the Servlet Specification version 2.2, which was released in 1999.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] At that time, both JavaScript and XML had already been developed, but the XMLHttpRequest object had only been recently introduced on Internet Explorer 5 as an ActiveX object.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] Beginning around the early 2000s, applications such as "Myspace (2003), Gmail (2004), Digg (2004), [and] Google Maps (2005)," started to make their client sides more and more interactive.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] A web page script is able to contact the server for storing/retrieving data without downloading an entire web page.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] The practice became known as Ajax in 2005.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] Eventually this was replaced by web APIs using JSON, accessed via JavaScript asynchronously on the client side.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] In earlier computing models like client-server, the processing load for the application was shared between code on the server and code installed on each client locally.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] In other words, an application had its own pre-compiled client program which served as its user interface and had to be separately installed on each user's personal computer.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] An upgrade to the server-side code of the application would typically also require an upgrade to the client-side code installed on each user workstation, adding to the support cost and decreasing productivity.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] Additionally, both the client and server components of the application were bound tightly to a particular computer architecture and operating system, which made porting them to other systems prohibitively expensive for all but the largest applications.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] Later, in 1995, Netscape introduced the client-side scripting language called JavaScript, which allowed programmers to add dynamic elements to the user interface that ran on the client side.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] Essentially, instead of sending data to the server in order to generate an entire web page, the embedded scripts of the downloaded page can perform various tasks such as input validation or showing/hiding parts of the page.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] Traditional PC applications are typically single-tiered, residing solely on the client machine.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] In contrast, web applications inherently facilitate a multi-tiered architecture.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] Though many variations are possible, the most common structure is the three-tiered application.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] In its most common form, the three tiers are called *presentation*, *application* and *storage*.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] The first tier, presentation, refers to a web browser itself.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] The second tier refers to any engine using dynamic web content technology (such as ASP, CGI, ColdFusion, Dart, JSP/Java, Node.js, PHP, Python or Ruby on Rails).
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] The third tier refers to a database that stores data and determines the structure of a user interface.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] Essentially, when using the three-tiered system, the web browser sends requests to the engine, which then services them by making queries and updates against the database and generates a user interface.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] The 3-tier solution may fall short when dealing with more complex applications, and may need to be replaced with the n-tiered approach; the greatest benefit of which is how business logic (which resides on the application tier) is broken down into a more fine-grained model.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] Another benefit would be to add an integration tier, which separates the data tier and provides an easy-to-use interface to access the data.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] For example, the client data would be accessed by calling a "list_clients()" function instead of making an SQL query directly against the client table on the database.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] This allows the underlying database to be replaced without making any change to the other tiers.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] There are some who view a web application as a two-tier architecture.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] This can be a "smart" client that performs all the work and queries a "dumb" server, or a "dumb" client that relies on a "smart" server.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] The client would handle the presentation tier, the server would have the database (storage tier), and the business logic (application tier) would be on one of them or on both.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] While this increases the scalability of the applications and separates the display and the database, it still does not allow for true specialization of layers, so most applications will outgrow this model.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] Security breaches on these kinds of applications are a major concern because it can involve both enterprise information and private customer data.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] Protecting these assets is an important part of any web application, and there are some key operational areas that must be included in the development process.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] This includes processes for authentication, authorization, asset handling, input, and logging and auditing.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] Building security into the applications from the beginning is sometimes more effective and less disruptive in the long run.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] Writing web applications is simplified with the use of web application frameworks.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] These frameworks facilitate rapid application development by allowing a development team to focus on the parts of their application which are unique to their goals without having to resolve common development issues such as user management.
[src:aws-lightsail/web-application] In addition, there is potential for the development of applications on Internet operating systems, although currently there are not many viable platforms that fit this model.
